  "text": "## Edition-Specific Import Path Handling in Rust Compiler\n\nThe Rust compiler implements edition-specific behavior for import paths and prelude handling, particularly between editions 2015/2018 and 2021. The key differences are:\n\n### 1. Prelude v1 vs Edition-Specific Exports\n\n**Core Prelude (library/core/src/prelude/mod.rs and library/std/src/prelude/mod.rs):**\n- All editions share the same base prelude (`v1.rs`) containing fundamental traits and types\n- `rust_2015`: Basic prelude items only\n- `rust_2018`: Same as 2015 (no additions at this level)\n- `rust_2021`: Adds `FromIterator`, `TryFrom`, and `TryInto` from core/std\n- `rust_2024`: Further additions including `Future` and `IntoFuture`\n\nThis is implemented in `library/core/src/prelude/mod.rs` (lines 14-72) and `library/std/src/prelude/mod.rs` (lines 116-162), where different edition-specific modules re-export base v1 items and add edition-specific additions.\n\n### 2. Edition-Based Macro_Use Difference\n\n**Standard Library Injection (compiler/rustc_builtin_macros/src/standard_library_imports.rs):**\nThe `inject()` function (lines 11-78) demonstrates the core edition-specific difference:\n- Line 42: `let ident_span = if edition >= Edition2018 { span } else { call_site };` - Different span handling for macro visibility\n- Lines 55-61: Edition-specific prelude module path selection:\n  - `Edition2015 => sym::rust_2015` (with root path prefix)\n  - `Edition2018 => sym::rust_2018`\n  - `Edition2021 => sym::rust_2021`\n  - `Edition2024 => sym::rust_2024`\n- Line 46: The `#[macro_use]` attribute is applied to the extern crate in all editions, but behaves differently based on resolver rules\n\n### 3. Resolver Behavior Changes Between Editions\n\n**Macro Resolution Scoping (compiler/rustc_resolve/src/ident.rs):**\nThe critical edition-dependent behavior is at line 160:\n```rust\nScope::MacroUsePrelude => use_prelude || rust_2015,\n```\n\nThis shows that:\n- In Edition 2015: `MacroUsePrelude` scope is always searched when resolving macros\n- In Editions 2018+: `MacroUsePrelude` scope is only searched if `use_prelude` is true (respecting `#[no_implicit_prelude]` attributes)\n\nThis difference means that in 2015, macros from `#[macro_use]` extern crates are automatically available. In 2018+, they follow normal prelude rules.\n\n**Macro Use Import Processing (compiler/rustc_resolve/src/build_reduced_graph.rs):**\nThe `process_macro_use_imports()` function (lines 1074-1168) and `add_macro_use_binding()` function (lines 1061-1071) handle how macros from `#[macro_use]` attributes are added to the module's macro namespace, with the MacroUsePrelude scope implementation providing the edition-dependent visibility rules.\n\n### 4. Prelude Collision Detection\n\n**Edition 2021 Prelude Collisions (compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/method/prelude_edition_lints.rs):**\nThis file handles linting for methods that will become ambiguous when new items are added to the prelude:\n- Line 37: `try_into` collision detection for 2021 edition\n- Lines 39-51: `poll` collision detection for 2024 edition\n- Lines 57-74: `into_iter` special handling for arrays\n\n### 5. Attribute Parsing for Macro Use\n\n**Macro Use Attribute Parser (compiler/rustc_attr_parsing/src/attributes/macro_attrs.rs):**\nThe `MacroUseParser` (lines 20-121) handles parsing of `#[macro_use]` attributes with support for both global imports (`#[macro_use]`) and selective imports (`#[macro_use(name1, name2)]`).\n\n### 6. Supporting Infrastructure\n\n- **compiler/rustc_resolve/src/lib.rs**: Defines the `Scope` enum including `MacroUsePrelude` variant (line 130), the fundamental scope for macro_use imports\n- **compiler/rustc_resolve/src/macros.rs**: Handles macro resolution logic with edition awareness\n- **compiler/rustc_expand/src/mbe/macro_rules.rs**: Contains edition-specific macro_rules handling (line 1495 checks `at_least_rust_2021()`)\n- **compiler/rustc_attr_parsing/src/attributes/no_implicit_prelude.rs**: Handles `#[no_implicit_prelude]` attribute that affects prelude visibility\n\nThe overall architecture shows that Rust's edition migration strategy carefully manages backward compatibility while allowing crates to opt into new prelude items by upgrading their edition, with the resolver's scope system providing the mechanism for edition-specific behavior."
